">

This may well be the official terminology used by IBM in its manuals.

But, as we know, IBM speaks of &quot;direct access storage devices&quot; when
everybody else says &quot;disk drives&quot;.

As for the word &quot;chad&quot;, this word comes from the world of
teletypewriter machines. The round pieces of teletypewriter tape that
result from punching holes in tape are called &quot;chad&quot;.

There are references, for example in _Datamation_ magazine, to the
term &quot;card chad&quot; being used for the normal contents of the chip bucket
on a model 029 keypunch.

Thus, even if it isn't official IBM terminology, I think one has to
admit that describing the punched-card equivalent of Timbits as &quot;chad&quot;
or at least &quot;card chad&quot; is a legitimate and attested usage. Even if
the waste produced from punching 90 and 96 column cards, as opposed to
80 column cards has greater chad nature.

John Savard
