Don't knock the PHB either.

Face it, PHB's fill many important functions where they have a lot
of power, including for purchasing, and they need technical support
they can handle too.

Their tasks are normally based on the commercial functioning of a
company; where the complexity is small to medium, and mostly
centered about doing it faster and for less money, and for as huge
a number of customers as possible. It must be repeatable, auditable,
and budgetable.

The PHBs are not very technically savvy. They struggle to understand
programming, and a language like C, or modern Fortran, or even Java
is way beyond what they can be expected to handle. PHB's thinking isn't
directed in this way at all.

But I have found that they can grok cobol pretty well; and they find
the listing support useful. (Listing of memory layout and cross reference
of usage is a mandatory part of cobol).

They don't mind the fuzzy syntax so much.

Cobol compilers have also gotten pretty good. Cobol programs need
not be monstrosities.

I suggest we don't bash COBOL, but that we make a _lot_ more cobol-like
languages where the PHB concepts are included in the language. I call
these &quot;surface languages&quot;. Lots of packages have surface languages as
a config language.

I can see the need for  a specific &quot;accountant and auditor language&quot; (AAAL?),
where t-accounts, transactions, audit trails, mandated rounding modes,
attribute associations and on-units for interest, credit violations, etc
are part of the language; and the language has a formal validation process.

It would then be a lot easier to write automation tools for these people,
when you can work from within their frame of reference (language, tools,
auditabinity) instead of having to recreate the reference frame for every
statement in the program.

Cobol has done a lot of this; and was amazingly early. Too bad we haven't
seen a good followup.

-- mrr
